","Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Renfrewshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Eaglesham, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Eaglesham, Renfrewshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Montgomery","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, Scottish, and northern Irish (of Norman origin): habitational name from Sainte-Foy-de-Montgomery and Saint-Germain-de-Montgomery (Calvados). In Ireland this surname was present in the medieval period, died out, and was then reintroduced from Scotland in the 17th century. It has been Gaelicized in Ireland as <b>Mac Iomaire</b> and in Scotland as <b>Mac Gumaraid</b>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Montgomery was born in 1334, in Scotland, her father, Alexander Montgomery, was 30 and her mother, Margaret Douglas, was 30. She had at least 2 sons and 3 daughters with Sir Thomas de Sempill II of Eliotstoun."},"et":{"1334–":"1334–Surnud","1334–Female":"1334–Surnud","1338–1398":"1338–1398","1332–1383":"1332–1383","1348–1400":"1348–1400","1358–Male":"1358–Surnud","1365–Female":"1365–Surnud","1367–Female":"1367–Surnud","1370–1453":"1370–1453","1305–1388":"1305–1388","1305–1374":"1305–1374","about 1370":"umbes 1370","1374":"1374","1383":"1383","1370":"1370","1305":"1305","1338":"1338","1348":"1348","1358":"1358","1334":"1334","1367":"1367","1400":"1400","1388":"1388","1365":"1365","1453":"1453","1332":"1332","1398":"1398","January 1, 1358":"1. jaanuar 1358","Eliotstoun, Renfrewshire, scotland":"Renfrewshire, Scotland","Renfrewshire, Strathclyde, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Renfrewshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Renfrewshire, Scotland